=========================================
C++17 if constexpr
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is if constexpr?

if constexpr is a C++17 feature that allows compile-time conditional branching.

Unlike a normal if statement, only the branch whose condition evaluates to true at compile time is compiled.

The other branch is discarded by the compiler.

Syntax

if constexpr(condition)
{
    // Compiled only if condition is true
}
else
{
    // Compiled only if condition is false
}

-----------------------------------------

2. Why was it introduced?

Before C++17, template code often required SFINAE (Substitution Failure Is Not An Error), std::enable_if, or 
tag dispatching to write different implementations for different types.

if constexpr provides a much simpler and more readable solution.

-----------------------------------------

3. Example

#include <iostream>
#include <type_traits>
using namespace std;

template<typename T>
void print(T x)
{
    if constexpr (is_integral_v<T>)
        cout << "Integer";
    else
        cout << "Other";
}

int main()
{
    print(10);
    print(3.14);
}

Output

Integer
Other

-----------------------------------------

4. What happens internally?

Call

print(10);

Compiler deduces

T = int

Condition becomes

if constexpr(true)

Compiler generates

void print(int x)
{
    cout << "Integer";
}

The else branch is completely discarded.

-----------------------------------------

Similarly

print(3.14);

Compiler deduces

T = double

Condition becomes

if constexpr(false)

Compiler generates

void print(double x)
{
    cout << "Other";
}

The first branch is discarded.

-----------------------------------------

5. Difference between if and if constexpr

Normal if

Both branches are compiled.

Condition is checked at runtime.

-----------------------------------------

if constexpr

Only one branch is compiled.

Condition is checked at compile time.

Unused branch is discarded.

-----------------------------------------

6. Why is this important?

Suppose

template<typename T>
void fun(T x)
{
    if (is_pointer_v<T>)
        cout << *x;
    else
        cout << x;
}

Now call

fun(10);

Although the runtime condition is false,

the compiler STILL compiles

cout << *x;

But

*x

is invalid for an int.

Compilation fails.

-----------------------------------------

Using if constexpr

template<typename T>
void fun(T x)
{
    if constexpr (is_pointer_v<T>)
        cout << *x;
    else
        cout << x;
}

Call

fun(10);

Compiler removes

cout << *x;

Only

cout << x;

is compiled.

Program compiles successfully.

-----------------------------------------

7. Real Example

template<typename T>
void display(T value)
{
    if constexpr(is_pointer_v<T>)
    {
        cout << "Pointer value = " << *value;
    }
    else
    {
        cout << "Value = " << value;
    }
}

int x = 100;

display(x);

display(&x);

Output

Value = 100

Pointer value = 100

-----------------------------------------

8. Why not use normal if?

Normal if compiles BOTH branches.

if constexpr compiles ONLY the valid branch.

This is the biggest advantage.

-----------------------------------------

9. Common Type Traits Used

is_integral_v<T>

is_pointer_v<T>

is_floating_point_v<T>

is_same_v<T,int>

is_arithmetic_v<T>

-----------------------------------------

10. Advantages

• Compile-time branching

• Eliminates invalid code

• Cleaner than SFINAE

• Easier to read

• Better compiler optimization

• No runtime overhead

-----------------------------------------

11. Where is it used?

• Generic programming

• Template libraries

• STL implementations

• Serialization libraries

• Logging frameworks

• Smart pointers

• Compile-time utilities

-----------------------------------------

12. Interview Questions

Q. What is if constexpr?

Answer

if constexpr is a C++17 feature that performs compile-time conditional branching. Only the branch whose 
condition evaluates to true is compiled, while the other branch is discarded.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which C++ version introduced if constexpr?

Answer

C++17

-----------------------------------------

Q. What problem does it solve?

Answer

Before C++17, template code required complex techniques like SFINAE, std::enable_if, or tag dispatching to select 
different implementations based on type. if constexpr makes this much simpler and more readable.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Difference between if and if constexpr?

Answer

Normal if

• Runtime decision
• Both branches are compiled

if constexpr

• Compile-time decision
• Only the valid branch is compiled

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why is if constexpr useful in templates?

Answer

Template code may contain operations that are valid only for certain types. if constexpr removes invalid 
branches during compilation, preventing compilation errors.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Does if constexpr have runtime overhead?

Answer

No.

The condition is evaluated at compile time, and the unused branch is removed completely.

-----------------------------------------

